title: For Sale/Trade:  Custom FN Mauser Mannlicher in 458x2 American w/ extras
location: York or Colonial Park, Harrisburg, Pennsylvania
postcontent:
You're looking at a custom big bore Mannlicher rifle built on a Belgium Fabrique National (FN) 1935 receiver.  This gem is chambered in .458x2" American, which is a shortened 458 Win Mag (a straight walled belted magnum case.)  Designed to drop ANY game in North America, this could be the ultimate brush cutter!

The conversion was likely done back in the 1960's, and was expertly completed.  The scope is a super-nice variable Bausch & Lomb BalVar 2.5-8x40mm on a rugged detachable mount.  The optics are great on this premium scope, with tapered cross-hairs.

The stock is a classic full-length walnut, w/ pronounced cheakpiece & metal nose cap.  Front ramp sight is in place.  Bore & rifling are great.  Trigger & bolt are well worked.  Sling points mounted.

The cons are few, the stock has a small chip/hairline at the rear of receiver.  The butt pad is old, hard, and a little mushed from standing on her tail.  Both things are easily fixed.  Bluing is around 85%.

The extras: 
1) A set of RCBS Custom Shop dies.  Lifetime warranty.  Worth at least $150 alone, these are what you need to make very affordable ammo.
2) Ammo.  I have 10 loaded rounds, all built on new brass with premium components.  The load is medium-strength, pushing a 350 gr. softpoint.  Perfect deer rounds...or elk...or moose...or bear.  LOL.
3) New reloading components:
Brass- Remington 458 Win Mag, untrimmed.
Bullets- Horonday 350 grain, round nose, soft point. 
Primers- Large Magnum Primers.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Jap Arisaka Type 99 with Full Mum/Cleaning Rod/Dust Cover**SOLD**
postcontent:
Up for sale is a WWII Jap Rifle from the Toyo Kogyo Arsenal. It is a Japanese Arisaka Type 99 rifle from the EARLY 32nd Series. This rifle is from a WWII Marine Vet estate. It is a true battlefield captured rifle and bears the full unmolested MUM. When I got the rifle it had been in storage for several years and not cared for. I took the rifle apart and cleaned it throughly. It is pretty pitted up as you can tell from the pictures. My Grandfather calls it "blood pitting". The bore is frosty but shows distinct lands and grooves. It does shoot and function as designed. The stock cleaned up really nice and is in good shape. No major dings and no cracks or splits. It is missing one of the bayonet lug screws. It has the full length cleaning rod. The serial numbers (405) match on the dust cover, bolt, extractor, safety knob, and firing pin. The bayonet lug is unmarked. The rifle serial number is pretty much unreadable due to some pitting. It reads 31XXX but if you get a jewelers loop you can pretty much make out the last three as 405. But because I can't be 100% sure I am not going to say it is 100% matching. You can be the judge. The rifle is just a really nice piece of WWII combat history. It is hard to find them with matching dust covers. If you want to buy the rifle I require full payment to be made by US POSTAL MONEY ORDER within seven days of the agreement to purchase.  Along with the money order I will need to see a signed copy of a valid FFL or C&R license of the individual you would like me to ship the rifle to for the transfer. I am not an FFL so make sure your FFL is willing to accept the rifle from me. If these instructions are not complied with the rifle will not be shipped.  Rifle will be shipped insured to you for $30 if you live in the lower 46 states.   It you want the rifle shipped to California, New York, or DC...Forget it.  Alaska and Hawaii will be a little more.

More pictures on request.

Email me with any questions you might have about the rifle.

Want to trade?  Let me know what you have.  Firearms related items only.

Semper Fi.

postcontent:
Your looking at a very nice custom built Ruger 10/22.


It has a 20" Butler Creek stainless steel barrel that has been reworked with a Bentz match grade chamber. Comes with a BSA platinum 6-24x44 scope. The bolt and trigger group have been completely worked. The hammer has been lightened, set screw in hammer to adjust the sear engagement, radius ground on the bottom of hammer for over travel, set screw in sear to reduce creep, set screw for adjustable trigger return pressure, over travel set screw in trigger gaurd, auto bolt release, The bolt has been chamfered, stoned and headspaced to .0425, firing pin has been staked, bolt buffer, set screws in the rear action to lock the trigger group and some misc polishing and stoning. It also has a extended bolt release and Kidd extended bolt handle. 


The stock is a custom one of benchrest stock. It has silver metallic base with ghost flames. The paint is in pretty good shape, not perfect however. The rifle was built to shoot, not sit in a safe. You won't be disappointed in this rifle. It's a real head turner. Will surely get attention at your local range.


The complete rifle is $900 firm w/2 10rd ruger factory mags. Will seperate the stock if you want just the barreled receiver with scope for $450obo.
